Household Survey Analysis - Parks Questions

Preliminary Results

Published

June 18, 2025

This document presents an initial analysis of the household survey responses from invited residents living within 0.1 mile (0.16 km) of Lafayette Park in Norfolk and Paradise Creek Nature Park in Portsmouth.

The survey itself was constructed using Qualtrics and participants were recruited using mailed postcards, email, and SMS text messaging. The household survey response rate was lower than expected, despite compensation in the form of a $35 gift card as a financial incentive and we received 93 responses from 486 invitations for a response rate of 19.1% percent.

In terms of age distribution, there were far more respondents from Portsmouth in the 60+ years category than from Norfolkâthe two distributions are otherwise similar. There appears to have been more parity in gender identity for Portsmouth respondents.

The responses to the How long have you lived in your current home? question skew towards longer-term residents in Norfolk. The majority of respondents (41%) are renters while in Norfolk that number is 33% and in Portsmouth 53% are renters.

Marital status is similarly distributed between Norfolk and Portsmouth respondents, but far more Portsmouth respondents have other dependents (i.e., not children) living in the household.

Educational attainment (i.e., respondents with a Bachelorâs degree or higher) is higher in Norfolk and this difference is statistically significant (kw = 7.26, p = 0.007). Reported incomes were higher in Norfolk while more Portsmouth respondents indicated they were âFinding it very difficult on present incomeâ.

There is a statistically significant difference in access to a garden with this being more likely among Norfolk respondents (kw = 5.01, p = 0.025).

Note the higher percentage of respondents with a health condition or disability in Portsmouth.

We see that a greater percentage of respondents living near Paradise Creek Nature Park reported that it would take 5 to 10 minutes to walk there from their home.

There are several sets of questions designed to capture peopleâs perceptions of the two parks considered as well as their satisfaction with those green spaces. The section below outlines how these question responses were coded to support analysis.

Perceptions of the Parks

For this battery of questions, all responses were collapsed from the original 5-point scale (1 = Strongly disagree, 2 = Somewhat disagree, 3 = Neither agree nor disagree, 4 = Somewhat agree, 5 = Strongly agree) to a 3-point scale 1 = Strongly or somewhat disagree, 2 = Neither agree nor disagree, 3 = Somewhat or strongly agree:

  • There is much to explore and discover here
  • This is a place to getaway from the things that usually demand my attention
  • I can see and enjoy wildlife in this local park
  • It is free from litter, graffiti and is well maintained
  • There is a range of good facilities
  • The facilities (e.g., playground equipment, sports fields) align with the needs of people who live in my neighborhood
  • It is attractive and pleasant to visit
  • I feel safe visiting during daylight hours

Surprisingly, there is no difference in responses to the I can see and enjoy wildlife in this local park question despite Paradise Creek Nature Park being more natural and forested.

There are statistically significant differences between Norfolk and Portsmouth respondents on the The facilities (e.g.,playground equipment, sports fields) align with the needs of people who live in my neighborhood question with responses higher on average in Norfolk. This seems to corroborate the hypothesis that the physical barrier that Granby Street and Victory Boulevard pose for residents is not the sole consideration when trying to understand differing usage rates. It could be that Cradock residents do not feel that the park and its facilities/characteristics fit their needs.

There are statistically significant differences between Norfolk and Portsmouth respondents on the I feel safe visiting during daylight hours question with responses higher on average in Norfolk. This appears to highlight a tension between greener, more heavily forested environments that are conducive to connecting with nature and safety concerns. While there are safety concerns voiced by Lafayette Park users, the environment is much more open with greater visibility and a higher number of other people in the park.

  • How satisfied are you with the quality of [Lafayette or Paradise Creek Nature] Park?

Usage of Local Park

The final set of questions asks about usage of the local park (e.g., frequency of visits by season), mode of transport, travel time, motivations for visiting, companions, and barriers to visiting. The visit frequency questions are described in greater detail below and are coded 0 = âNeverâ, 1 = âAbout once a monthâ, 2 = âSeveral times a monthâ, 3 = âOnce a weekâ, 4 = âSeveral times a weekâ, 5 = âEverydayâ :

  • How often do you visit this park from October to March?
  • How often do you visit park from April to September?

Other related questions include:

  • How do you usually get to [Lafayette or Paradise Creek Nature] Park? 0 = âOther, please explainâ, 1 = âCarâ, 2 = âBikeâ, 3 = âWalkingâ
  • How long does it take to get there by the mode above? A higher value indicates greater travel time
  • What are your two main reasons for visiting [Lafayette or Paradise Creek Nature] Park?
  • Who do you usually go to [Lafayette or Paradise Creek Nature] Park with?
  • What prevents you from visiting [Lafayette or Paradise Creek Nature] Park?

We can see from the tests above that there are statistically significant differences in the reported frequency of park visits during the spring and summer months with Lafayette Park visits being higher on average. There is no evidence of significant differences in the reported frequency of park visits during the fall and winter.

There are statistically significant differences in travel mode to the the parks with more active modes (i.e., biking and walking) more common for Norfolk participants visiting Lafayette Park.

The charts presented below visualize the responses to several questions. First all the responses are pooled and then they broken out by each of the two parks of interest. The first few charts below focus on why respondents visit these parks.



Overall, âTo get some fresh airâ and âTo relax or thinkâ account for 50% of all responses. If we look only at responses related to Lafayette Park, teh top three response are the same but we see its use as a gathering place and social importance, while a greater percentage of Paradise Creek Nature Park respondents cite seeing wildlife or birds as a motivation for visiting.

The charts below extend the visualization above and are an attempt to distill the reasons given for visiting the park into one of five broad categoriesâExercise, Instrumental (e.g., passing through to a destination, walking the dog), Nature, Restorative, and Social.



It appears that reported motivations for visiting the two parks are different consistent with our understanding of the functions they best support (e.g., restorative versus social). One does not simply end up in Paradise Creek Nature Park and the lower instrumental visit category suggests that those visits may be more intentional? Restorative visits were more prevalent in Lafayette Park than I had anticiptated.

The charts below explore whether respondents typically visit alone or with companions.



We can see that overall, over two-thirds of the reported visits were made alone. Visits with children were more prevalent in Lafayette Park which is interesting given the presence of a playground at both locations.

In terms of barriers to visiting the parks, a lack of time to visit, safety concerns, and barriers to pedestrian access (i.e., major roads) were cited by respondents in Norfolk and Portsmouth.

Correlations with Other Respondent Characteristics

An OLS regression was fit with each of the park perception responses as the dependent variableâthis uses the collapsed 3-point scale.

The only significant predictor of responses to the There is much to explore and discover here question was whether the respondent indicated that they preferred to visit a different park (R2 = 0.10).

Preferring another park was the only significant predictor of the response to the The facilities align with the needs of people who live in my neighborhood question (R2 = 0.03).

Linear regression with the collapsed scale variables is not telling us very much.

Logistic regression using the park quality question and the prefer another park question as dependent variables also did not reveal any statistically significant patterns.
